\begin_layout Section*
Minimum distance between points
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One of the reason why estimating K and g(r) is difficult is that for small
 radii (below 10
\begin_inset Formula $^{-2}$
\end_inset

), we can find very few observed distances between pairs of points.
 As a first proxy, we want to estimate the minimum expected distance between
 points when they are uniformly distributed.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 dimensions, the probability distribution of the nearest-neighbour distribution
 follows 
\begin_inset Formula $f(r)=db_{d}\lambda r^{d-1}\exp(-b_{d}r^{_{d}}\lambda)$
\end_inset

).
 If we want to find the distribution of the minimum distance between 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 realized points of a Poisson process with intensity 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

, we can write:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{ccc}
Pr(\min(R_{1},...,R_{n})>r) & = & Pr(R_{1}>r,...,R_{n}>r)\\
 & = & \Pi_{i}Pr(R_{1}>r)\\
 & = & \Pi_{i}\exp(-b_{d}r^{_{d}}\lambda)\\
 & = & \exp(-b_{d}r^{_{d}}\Sigma_{i}\lambda)
\end{array}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can then conclude that the distribution of the minimum distance follows
 the same distribution as the nearest neighbour distribution, but with intensity
 
\begin_inset Formula $n\lambda$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "clark_generalization_1979"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 show that a variable with probability distribution (with notations changed
 to fit our own) 
\begin_inset Formula $f(r)=\frac{d\lambda\pi^{d/2}r^{d-1}}{\Gamma(\frac{d}{2}+1)}\exp(-\frac{\lambda\pi^{d/2}r^{d}}{\Gamma(\frac{d}{2}+1)})=d\lambda b_{d}r^{d-1}\exp(-\lambda b_{d}r^{d})$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Remember that 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{d}$
\end_inset

, the volume of the unit sphere is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\pi^{d/2}}{\Gamma(\frac{d}{2}+1)}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 has a mean of 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\left(\Gamma(\frac{d}{2}+1)\right)^{1/d}\Gamma(\frac{1}{d}+1)}{\lambda^{1/d}\pi^{1/2}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With intensity 
\begin_inset Formula $n\lambda$
\end_inset

, we can write 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\left(\Gamma(\frac{d}{2}+1)\right)^{1/d}\Gamma(\frac{1}{d}+1)}{(n\lambda)^{1/d}\pi^{1/2}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 3D, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=(n\lambda)^{-1/3}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\left(\Gamma(\frac{3}{2}+1)\right)^{1/3}\Gamma(\frac{1}{3}+1)}{\pi^{1/2}}=(n\lambda)^{-1/3}\left(\frac{3}{2}\Gamma(3/2)\right)^{1/3}\frac{1}{3}\Gamma(1/3)\frac{1}{\pi^{1/2}}\approx0.554\frac{1}{(n\lambda)^{1/3}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This needs to be taken into account when defining 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 As a first proxy, using 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=$
\end_inset

10
\begin_inset Formula $^{4}$
\end_inset

cm
\begin_inset Formula $^{-3}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n\approx$
\end_inset

10
\begin_inset Formula $^{4}$
\end_inset

 if we model a 1 cm
\begin_inset Formula $^{3}$
\end_inset

 cube, we would expect the smallest distance to be 
\begin_inset Formula $1.2\times10^{-3}$
\end_inset

 cm.
\end_layout

